WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.297
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:05.587 --> 00:00:07.920
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Thank you
guys so much for having me.

00:00:07.920 --> 00:00:09.628
SPEAKER: Yeah, we're
excited to have you.

00:00:09.628 --> 00:00:12.160
So would love to just learn
a little bit more about

00:00:12.160 --> 00:00:14.160
Mike, the kid from
Pittsburgh, turning

00:00:14.160 --> 00:00:17.170
into Chef Michael Solomonov,
the James Beard Award winner.

00:00:17.170 --> 00:00:19.000
Did you always know
that this was something

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:20.085
that you were going to be?

00:00:20.085 --> 00:00:21.460
Did you always
want to be a chef?

00:00:21.460 --> 00:00:25.060
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: No, I was a
really, really difficult eater

00:00:25.060 --> 00:00:27.340
as a kid, ironically.

00:00:27.340 --> 00:00:30.770
And I was going to be--

00:00:30.770 --> 00:00:34.390
I wanted to be an
actor when I was a kid.

00:00:34.390 --> 00:00:36.110
I wanted to be a photographer.

00:00:36.110 --> 00:00:39.520
I went to college
briefly with the intent

00:00:39.520 --> 00:00:42.130
of getting into photography.

00:00:42.130 --> 00:00:46.544
And then ended up only
smoking pot, and snowboarding,

00:00:46.544 --> 00:00:47.710
and dropping out of college.

00:00:47.710 --> 00:00:48.320
SPEAKER: Nice.

00:00:48.320 --> 00:00:50.445
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: And then
I moved back to Israel.

00:00:50.445 --> 00:00:51.760
My family and I had moved--

00:00:51.760 --> 00:00:53.230
I was born in Israel,
grew up in Pittsburgh,

00:00:53.230 --> 00:00:55.063
and then we moved back
when I was, like, 15.

00:00:55.063 --> 00:00:59.570
So I dropped out of school,
and moved back to Israel,

00:00:59.570 --> 00:01:03.289
and walked up and down the
main street in the town

00:01:03.289 --> 00:01:05.830
that we lived in, in this little
town called Kfar Saba, which

00:01:05.830 --> 00:01:07.600
is north of Tel Aviv.

00:01:07.600 --> 00:01:12.760
And just asked people in very
broken Hebrew and English

00:01:12.760 --> 00:01:15.130
if they needed somebody
to work for them.

00:01:15.130 --> 00:01:17.110
And I got a job in a bakery.

00:01:17.110 --> 00:01:18.790
And that's where
I started cooking.

00:01:18.790 --> 00:01:19.580
SPEAKER: Amazing.

00:01:19.580 --> 00:01:20.580
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Yeah.

00:01:20.580 --> 00:01:23.290
SPEAKER: And from
that bakery, what were

00:01:23.290 --> 00:01:25.840
your biggest lessons learned?

00:01:25.840 --> 00:01:28.160
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
Well, I wasn't

00:01:28.160 --> 00:01:36.650
used to working and working
hard or working legitimately.

00:01:36.650 --> 00:01:38.570
So I learned a lot about--

00:01:38.570 --> 00:01:41.390
I mean, probably the most
important lessons of my life

00:01:41.390 --> 00:01:42.170
happened there.

00:01:44.690 --> 00:01:48.320
I couldn't talk my way into
anything, because nobody there

00:01:48.320 --> 00:01:50.270
cared where I really came from.

00:01:50.270 --> 00:01:53.810
They were happy at that
time to have not only

00:01:53.810 --> 00:01:57.650
an immigrant worker, but also
an immigrant American worker.

00:01:57.650 --> 00:01:59.020
It was like a twofer for them.

00:01:59.020 --> 00:02:03.880
It was like this status
symbol that they had this guy.

00:02:03.880 --> 00:02:09.680
And it was right around the
Clinton, Monica Lewinsky

00:02:09.680 --> 00:02:10.610
scandal thing.

00:02:10.610 --> 00:02:14.011
So they would be like,
yeah, Bill Clinton, huh?

00:02:14.011 --> 00:02:14.510
You know?

00:02:14.510 --> 00:02:19.010
And I was like, I don't
know him personally.

00:02:19.010 --> 00:02:20.300
And I don't speak any Hebrew.

00:02:20.300 --> 00:02:21.905
Can you just tell me what to do?

00:02:25.400 --> 00:02:30.050
I learned a lot about
myself and about what

00:02:30.050 --> 00:02:32.900
it was like to really
have to work hard.

00:02:32.900 --> 00:02:38.210
And everybody there was
from somewhere else.

00:02:38.210 --> 00:02:42.830
And culturally, it was
just really exciting.

00:02:42.830 --> 00:02:45.350
And it was at the lowest level--

00:02:45.350 --> 00:02:48.830
literally, I was taking out
garbage bags full of trash,

00:02:48.830 --> 00:02:52.400
scrubbing sheet trays
for 10 hours at a time,

00:02:52.400 --> 00:02:55.340
chasing rats around
with a pizza cutter,

00:02:55.340 --> 00:03:00.750
and occasionally would
get to do cool stuff.

00:03:00.750 --> 00:03:03.979
And I learned Hebrew, and I
learned a little bit of Arabic,

00:03:03.979 --> 00:03:05.270
and I learned a bit of Russian.

00:03:07.980 --> 00:03:10.280
My family's from
Bulgaria before Israel,

00:03:10.280 --> 00:03:12.290
or like half of my family is.

00:03:12.290 --> 00:03:18.180
And I learned what the
sort of social cues

00:03:18.180 --> 00:03:20.492
of Bulgarian Jewish
immigrants as it

00:03:20.492 --> 00:03:22.200
related to everybody
else-- because there

00:03:22.200 --> 00:03:24.600
were Venezuelan immigrants.

00:03:24.600 --> 00:03:27.330
There was Muslim Arabs.

00:03:27.330 --> 00:03:28.980
There were Christian Arabs.

00:03:28.980 --> 00:03:31.380
And it was just awesome.

00:03:31.380 --> 00:03:37.360
And I remember the owner of the
bakery took me to his house.

00:03:37.360 --> 00:03:39.510
And I thought he was making
me lunch or whatever.

00:03:39.510 --> 00:03:42.045
And he made me
clean up his garden.

00:03:42.045 --> 00:03:43.260
SPEAKER: [LAUGHS]

00:03:43.260 --> 00:03:46.920
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: And then
afterwards, we drank coffee.

00:03:46.920 --> 00:03:50.900
And he was asking me if I
wanted to close the bakery,

00:03:50.900 --> 00:03:53.460
if that would be my new
task that I would enjoy.

00:03:53.460 --> 00:03:56.160
The word for bakery in
Hebrew is "ma'afiyah,"

00:03:56.160 --> 00:03:58.180
which I thought was "mafia."

00:03:58.180 --> 00:04:01.650
So he was having a conversation
with me for 45 minutes,

00:04:01.650 --> 00:04:03.772
and I was like, am
I being in the mob?

00:04:03.772 --> 00:04:05.480
Like, is that what's
happening right now?

00:04:05.480 --> 00:04:06.460
SPEAKER: Is that my
next career move?

00:04:06.460 --> 00:04:07.320
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Because
I didn't know that ma'afiyah

00:04:07.320 --> 00:04:08.070
meant "bakery."

00:04:08.070 --> 00:04:10.602
So I thought I'd
left there with--

00:04:10.602 --> 00:04:11.310
SPEAKER: New job.

00:04:11.310 --> 00:04:12.476
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: --status.

00:04:12.476 --> 00:04:17.550
But really, I got a 20-agorat
raise, which is like $0.07.

00:04:17.550 --> 00:04:20.850
So I was making the equivalent
of $3 an hour there.

00:04:20.850 --> 00:04:21.750
SPEAKER: Awesome.

00:04:21.750 --> 00:04:22.500
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
And it was amazing.

00:04:22.500 --> 00:04:23.260
I loved it.

00:04:23.260 --> 00:04:28.530
I fell in love with
the camaraderie

00:04:28.530 --> 00:04:30.900
and the legitimate work.

00:04:30.900 --> 00:04:34.410
And I'd come from this
sort of upper middle class,

00:04:34.410 --> 00:04:36.930
middle class background
in the States.

00:04:36.930 --> 00:04:40.110
And my values were skewed.

00:04:40.110 --> 00:04:43.060
So it was really cool to do
that and to learn something.

00:04:43.060 --> 00:04:46.890
And at the bakery, we made
a bunch of cool things.

00:04:46.890 --> 00:04:47.490
Challah.

00:04:47.490 --> 00:04:49.059
Everybody eats challah.

00:04:49.059 --> 00:04:50.850
First of all, nobody
in Israel gives a shit

00:04:50.850 --> 00:04:52.590
about carbohydrates at all.

00:04:52.590 --> 00:04:55.067
So they don't know
what Atkins is.

00:04:55.067 --> 00:04:57.150
Anytime you go over to
someone's house over there,

00:04:57.150 --> 00:04:58.775
and they're like,
come over for coffee,

00:04:58.775 --> 00:05:02.100
it is like platters
of cakes, right?

00:05:02.100 --> 00:05:05.370
And regardless of how
religious you are,

00:05:05.370 --> 00:05:08.400
everybody eats challah,
basically, on Fridays.

00:05:08.400 --> 00:05:12.870
So I was used to this
alternative subculture

00:05:12.870 --> 00:05:15.480
of being a recluse
pothead in the States.

00:05:15.480 --> 00:05:17.610
But in Israel,
working in a bakery

00:05:17.610 --> 00:05:20.950
means that you're basically
the center of town on Friday.

00:05:20.950 --> 00:05:24.720
So we'd go in Friday
morning at 2:00 AM

00:05:24.720 --> 00:05:26.480
and make challahs
for like 14 hours.

00:05:26.480 --> 00:05:28.260
And every single
person in the town

00:05:28.260 --> 00:05:30.900
would come and participate.

00:05:30.900 --> 00:05:32.670
So you were part of
something, right?

00:05:32.670 --> 00:05:35.650
And then my grandmother,
who was probably like--

00:05:35.650 --> 00:05:36.970
I know this is super cliched--

00:05:36.970 --> 00:05:38.990
but the reason I
probably love food

00:05:38.990 --> 00:05:42.420
or love the heritage of
the food that I cook,

00:05:42.420 --> 00:05:45.600
would make bourekas, which
are this Balkan pastry that

00:05:45.600 --> 00:05:47.610
come all the way
from medieval Spain

00:05:47.610 --> 00:05:50.310
through the Ottoman
Empire to Israel.

00:05:50.310 --> 00:05:53.880
And I got to make
thousands of them a day.

00:05:53.880 --> 00:05:57.445
And it was like the one thing
that I loved eating as a kid.

00:05:57.445 --> 00:05:59.820
And it was the way that I
could relate to my grandmother.

00:05:59.820 --> 00:06:04.830
So to be part of something on
this hyper social, but also

00:06:04.830 --> 00:06:07.320
hyper spiritual
level was something

00:06:07.320 --> 00:06:08.910
I had never really experienced.

00:06:08.910 --> 00:06:09.630
SPEAKER: Amazing.

00:06:09.630 --> 00:06:10.230
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Yeah.

00:06:10.230 --> 00:06:11.188
SPEAKER: Real question.

00:06:11.188 --> 00:06:14.100
Boureka is filled with spinach,
with cheese, with potato.

00:06:14.100 --> 00:06:15.315
What's your favorite filling?

00:06:15.315 --> 00:06:17.340
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Feta cheese
with a shitload of sesame

00:06:17.340 --> 00:06:17.881
on top--best.

00:06:17.881 --> 00:06:18.770
SPEAKER: Cool.

00:06:18.770 --> 00:06:18.910
Awesome.

00:06:18.910 --> 00:06:21.368
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: But all of
them are really, really good.

00:06:21.368 --> 00:06:26.160
And they tell the story
of real Israeli cuisine.

00:06:26.160 --> 00:06:28.117
And it's fascinating.

00:06:28.117 --> 00:06:28.700
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:06:28.700 --> 00:06:29.940
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Do you guys
want to hear the real story?

00:06:29.940 --> 00:06:30.700
SPEAKER: Let's hear it.

00:06:30.700 --> 00:06:31.380
You're tempting us.

00:06:31.380 --> 00:06:31.452
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: OK, good.

00:06:31.452 --> 00:06:32.952
And then I'm done
after this, right?

00:06:32.952 --> 00:06:33.760
No.

00:06:33.760 --> 00:06:36.660
So my grandmother, her
maiden name before Solomonov,

00:06:36.660 --> 00:06:39.620
was Toledo, which is
from the town in Spain.

00:06:39.620 --> 00:06:44.340
Post-Inquisition, they
peaced out of Spain.

00:06:44.340 --> 00:06:46.350
And they brought with
them this laminated dough.

00:06:46.350 --> 00:06:48.683
And everyone thinks that the
French puff pastry actually

00:06:48.683 --> 00:06:53.130
comes from the Sephardic
Jews in medieval Spain.

00:06:53.130 --> 00:06:55.710
So they brought
with them this dough

00:06:55.710 --> 00:06:58.560
to the Balkans,
where they settled.

00:06:58.560 --> 00:07:03.240
And the Ottomans came
in and took over,

00:07:03.240 --> 00:07:05.700
like they did a lot of
the world at that time.

00:07:05.700 --> 00:07:11.520
And they started stuffing this
laminated pastry with what

00:07:11.520 --> 00:07:14.160
we think is Bulgarian feta.

00:07:14.160 --> 00:07:18.690
And then the Bulgarians
overthrew the Ottomans

00:07:18.690 --> 00:07:21.040
using Russian
families to help arm

00:07:21.040 --> 00:07:23.910
them, which is why my last
name is Solomonov, actually.

00:07:23.910 --> 00:07:25.320
Everyone thinks I'm Russian.

00:07:25.320 --> 00:07:27.240
I don't speak any Russian.

00:07:27.240 --> 00:07:29.550
And in fact, the
last name was Bahar.

00:07:29.550 --> 00:07:32.820
But to honor the
Russian families that

00:07:32.820 --> 00:07:36.750
helped arm these
Bulgarians in Varna,

00:07:36.750 --> 00:07:38.730
they all took
Russian last names.

00:07:38.730 --> 00:07:40.710
And then in 1948, they
all moved to Israel,

00:07:40.710 --> 00:07:43.950
bringing with them this
savory pastry, which is now

00:07:43.950 --> 00:07:46.155
on every single street
corner in Israel,

00:07:46.155 --> 00:07:47.980
which is awesome, right?

00:07:47.980 --> 00:07:50.100
SPEAKER: Yeah, great story.

00:07:50.100 --> 00:07:53.370
So given that you had
a stint in Israel,

00:07:53.370 --> 00:07:54.840
came back to the
States, how do you

00:07:54.840 --> 00:07:56.489
think that kind
of back-and-forth

00:07:56.489 --> 00:07:57.780
has influenced your food today?

00:07:57.780 --> 00:07:59.280
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
I actually think,

00:07:59.280 --> 00:08:02.140
going back-- so I didn't move
to Israel to become a chef.

00:08:02.140 --> 00:08:03.390
I just ended up working there.

00:08:03.390 --> 00:08:05.700
And then I worked at a
little cafe after the bakery.

00:08:05.700 --> 00:08:10.380
And I was like, wow, creating
things with my hands is fun.

00:08:10.380 --> 00:08:11.700
I like the intensity.

00:08:11.700 --> 00:08:14.370
I like the people-pleasing.

00:08:14.370 --> 00:08:15.700
I'm going to become a chef.

00:08:15.700 --> 00:08:17.700
And it wasn't my intention
to cook Israeli food.

00:08:17.700 --> 00:08:20.550
I moved back to the States,
and went to culinary school,

00:08:20.550 --> 00:08:22.961
and then worked in a bunch
of European restaurants

00:08:22.961 --> 00:08:23.460
or whatever.

00:08:23.460 --> 00:08:25.350
And I thought that's what--

00:08:25.350 --> 00:08:30.340
at that time in the '90s, or
the late '90s, early 2000s,

00:08:30.340 --> 00:08:35.679
everybody would go to school
or work and then go to Europe.

00:08:35.679 --> 00:08:40.690
And it was either San
Sebastian, Spain or France.

00:08:40.690 --> 00:08:42.610
That's kind of where
everybody was going.

00:08:42.610 --> 00:08:45.700
And that's just what
I thought I would do.

00:08:45.700 --> 00:08:47.230
And then I ended up not.

00:08:47.230 --> 00:08:51.170
I ended up going back to
visit my family in Israel.

00:08:51.170 --> 00:08:53.330
One of many things happened.

00:08:53.330 --> 00:08:56.050
And I just sort of was--

00:08:56.050 --> 00:08:58.896
I don't know.

00:08:58.896 --> 00:09:00.520
Sitting down at a
restaurant and having

00:09:00.520 --> 00:09:02.740
20 different little
dishes come out

00:09:02.740 --> 00:09:06.050
that represent 20
different countries,

00:09:06.050 --> 00:09:09.940
and the sort of music of it
all, and the choreography,

00:09:09.940 --> 00:09:12.850
and the live fuel, and
everything over charcoal,

00:09:12.850 --> 00:09:14.320
and spices that
you've never heard

00:09:14.320 --> 00:09:18.020
of that represent the
spice trade, the Silk Road,

00:09:18.020 --> 00:09:21.850
2,000 years of
post-Babylon diaspora,

00:09:21.850 --> 00:09:25.930
Palestinian cooking from the
West Bank, from the Levant,

00:09:25.930 --> 00:09:29.740
from Gaza, the
Shabbat dinners that

00:09:29.740 --> 00:09:34.330
include 100 different
cultures all mushed together,

00:09:34.330 --> 00:09:38.580
it was like, why do I
need to go to France?

00:09:38.580 --> 00:09:41.320
Why do I need to go to Spain?

00:09:41.320 --> 00:09:45.610
At that time, ironically, tapas
was a big thing in Philly.

00:09:45.610 --> 00:09:48.130
And I was like, well, people
understand small plates

00:09:48.130 --> 00:09:52.240
because of tapas, which is
funny, because mezze predates

00:09:52.240 --> 00:09:53.499
tapas by, like, 2,000 years.

00:09:53.499 --> 00:09:54.040
But whatever.

00:09:57.900 --> 00:10:00.730
And I think that while that was
happening, people in Israel,

00:10:00.730 --> 00:10:03.760
instead of cooks in
Israel going to Europe,

00:10:03.760 --> 00:10:06.520
or going to Asia or the States,
and then coming back to Israel

00:10:06.520 --> 00:10:11.320
to open up French restaurants or
whatever, they were like, well,

00:10:11.320 --> 00:10:15.850
going to have Shabbat dinner at
my grandparents' means Polish,

00:10:15.850 --> 00:10:19.157
Moroccan, Yemenite,
and Romanian.

00:10:19.157 --> 00:10:19.990
It's all right here.

00:10:19.990 --> 00:10:22.090
I don't need to go
anywhere else for it.

00:10:22.090 --> 00:10:24.670
So we decided to open
an Israeli restaurant.

00:10:24.670 --> 00:10:27.640
And we didn't know
what that meant,

00:10:27.640 --> 00:10:29.110
because everyone was like--

00:10:29.110 --> 00:10:29.860
what do you think?

00:10:29.860 --> 00:10:31.526
When somebody says
there's a restaurant,

00:10:31.526 --> 00:10:35.132
they're like, falafel, right,
or shawarma, or hummus, which--

00:10:35.132 --> 00:10:37.090
we would have made a lot
more money had we just

00:10:37.090 --> 00:10:39.910
opened up those places.

00:10:39.910 --> 00:10:45.194
So we had to convince people
and answer the question--

00:10:45.194 --> 00:10:46.735
everyone was like,
isn't it political

00:10:46.735 --> 00:10:47.985
to open an Israeli restaurant?

00:10:47.985 --> 00:10:49.590
And I'm like, I don't know.

00:10:49.590 --> 00:10:50.880
I'm Israeli.

00:10:50.880 --> 00:10:53.550
I think that's kind of
a big, broad question.

00:10:53.550 --> 00:10:56.340
So we decided to
open what people call

00:10:56.340 --> 00:10:57.720
a modern Israeli restaurant.

00:10:57.720 --> 00:11:00.780
Even though we cook
everything over charcoal

00:11:00.780 --> 00:11:02.940
and make bread in a
wood-burning oven.

00:11:02.940 --> 00:11:05.370
The cooking methods
are quite primitive.

00:11:05.370 --> 00:11:10.315
But the idea of this
global Israeli food

00:11:10.315 --> 00:11:12.690
going to different places and
being sort of reinterpreted

00:11:12.690 --> 00:11:14.196
is what I think makes it modern.

00:11:14.196 --> 00:11:15.070
SPEAKER: Interesting.

00:11:15.070 --> 00:11:16.200
Love that.

00:11:16.200 --> 00:11:19.180
So not only did you have
an uber-successful Israeli

00:11:19.180 --> 00:11:19.680
restaurant.

00:11:19.680 --> 00:11:22.740
You also have a donut empire.

00:11:22.740 --> 00:11:24.960
You have a few cookbooks.

00:11:24.960 --> 00:11:28.470
How do you decide what
ideas are worth sticking

00:11:28.470 --> 00:11:31.050
to or really worth pursuing?

00:11:31.050 --> 00:11:32.670
I'm sure you get,
in your head, a lot

00:11:32.670 --> 00:11:34.320
of different concepts, ideas.

00:11:34.320 --> 00:11:37.674
What makes something
worth pursuing to you?

00:11:37.674 --> 00:11:39.840
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: I think
that's a really difficult

00:11:39.840 --> 00:11:43.920
question to answer, because
I think that as much as one

00:11:43.920 --> 00:11:46.860
can strategize-- the secret
to any of this success

00:11:46.860 --> 00:11:51.600
is having a brilliant
business partner or partners,

00:11:51.600 --> 00:11:53.940
which I've been lucky to have.

00:11:53.940 --> 00:11:59.207
I think that you have to make
a lot of really bad decisions.

00:11:59.207 --> 00:12:01.290
You don't wake up in the
morning, and you're like,

00:12:01.290 --> 00:12:02.880
we're going to have
a donut empire.

00:12:02.880 --> 00:12:06.600
What really happened is Zahav
almost closed its first year.

00:12:06.600 --> 00:12:08.640
We opened another restaurant.

00:12:08.640 --> 00:12:12.720
So we opened a modern Israeli
restaurant in 2008 right

00:12:12.720 --> 00:12:16.740
after Wachovia, AIG went under.

00:12:16.740 --> 00:12:18.690
I was in drug rehab.

00:12:18.690 --> 00:12:21.210
And the Phillies were
winning the World Series,

00:12:21.210 --> 00:12:24.210
which is awesome if
you have a restaurant

00:12:24.210 --> 00:12:27.540
or bar with a TV in it, not if
you have an Israeli restaurant.

00:12:27.540 --> 00:12:31.380
And the elections
were happening.

00:12:31.380 --> 00:12:32.880
Nobody wanted to go out and eat.

00:12:32.880 --> 00:12:36.420
And the economy
was falling apart.

00:12:36.420 --> 00:12:41.070
And when you're doing chopped
Israeli salad in February

00:12:41.070 --> 00:12:43.440
in eastern Pennsylvania,
it's a little bit

00:12:43.440 --> 00:12:46.656
difficult for the
customer, I guess,

00:12:46.656 --> 00:12:48.030
to understand what
was happening.

00:12:48.030 --> 00:12:49.770
So we almost went under.

00:12:49.770 --> 00:12:52.350
It was an awful year
for many reasons.

00:12:52.350 --> 00:12:54.810
And then we decided to
open a barbecue restaurant,

00:12:54.810 --> 00:12:58.379
thinking that it would be low
labor, low cost, low tech.

00:12:58.379 --> 00:12:59.670
All of those things were wrong.

00:12:59.670 --> 00:13:02.730
We opened, brisket
was $1.90 a pound.

00:13:02.730 --> 00:13:06.360
When we sold the restaurant,
brisket was at $5.00 a pound.

00:13:06.360 --> 00:13:08.929
Smoking meat is
very difficult. We

00:13:08.929 --> 00:13:10.470
were doing it like
Texas style, which

00:13:10.470 --> 00:13:12.930
is closer to the Jewish
brisket that we grew up with.

00:13:12.930 --> 00:13:15.330
Most people don't like that.

00:13:15.330 --> 00:13:17.880
Most people, actually,
go anywhere in the South,

00:13:17.880 --> 00:13:21.180
have barbecue once, and think
that that is what barbecue is.

00:13:21.180 --> 00:13:23.719
So we didn't have pulled
pork for the first two years

00:13:23.719 --> 00:13:25.010
even though everyone was like--

00:13:25.010 --> 00:13:25.580
SPEAKER: Where's
the pulled pork?

00:13:25.580 --> 00:13:26.520
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
--where's the pulled pork?

00:13:26.520 --> 00:13:27.330
I love pulled pork.

00:13:27.330 --> 00:13:29.790
And we're like, no, no,
no, they don't know.

00:13:29.790 --> 00:13:31.200
[LAUGHTER]

00:13:31.200 --> 00:13:33.330
The reality is
you need to listen

00:13:33.330 --> 00:13:35.340
to what your customers want.

00:13:35.340 --> 00:13:38.910
And it doesn't matter what the
tradition is, because tradition

00:13:38.910 --> 00:13:41.550
in Texas is different
just like it

00:13:41.550 --> 00:13:44.010
is when you make
pasta in Piedmont,

00:13:44.010 --> 00:13:46.765
depending on what side of
the street you live on.

00:13:46.765 --> 00:13:51.060
And the other thing is we
weren't emotionally invested

00:13:51.060 --> 00:13:52.120
into what it was.

00:13:52.120 --> 00:13:54.280
It didn't mean
the same as Zahav.

00:13:54.280 --> 00:13:56.940
So we started a donut
empire because we

00:13:56.940 --> 00:13:59.220
had two restaurants that
were going to go under,

00:13:59.220 --> 00:14:02.040
that were huge.

00:14:02.040 --> 00:14:05.910
My partner, Steve, and I
met three other people.

00:14:05.910 --> 00:14:09.780
We all threw in a very small
amount of money, whatever

00:14:09.780 --> 00:14:12.240
we were kind of willing
to lose at that time,

00:14:12.240 --> 00:14:14.910
because we wanted to do a new
project, and we were bored,

00:14:14.910 --> 00:14:19.020
and the big-box restaurants in
Philly were going to kill us.

00:14:19.020 --> 00:14:21.720
So we found a
600-square-foot restaurant

00:14:21.720 --> 00:14:23.700
with three other people.

00:14:23.700 --> 00:14:27.840
Two of them brought the first
wave of fancy coffee to Philly.

00:14:27.840 --> 00:14:30.090
The other person was
a social media whiz.

00:14:30.090 --> 00:14:31.470
Steve and I knew food.

00:14:31.470 --> 00:14:35.730
And we opened Federal
Donuts with, like, $30,000.

00:14:35.730 --> 00:14:37.591
And then on day two--

00:14:37.591 --> 00:14:40.500
well, day one and day two, we
ran out of donuts in an hour,

00:14:40.500 --> 00:14:44.870
and we had people standing
in line for chicken

00:14:44.870 --> 00:14:48.110
at 11:00 AM, when
we started at noon.

00:14:48.110 --> 00:14:51.500
And we were like, oh, we might
actually be on to something.

00:14:51.500 --> 00:14:53.960
So it was kind of like we had
nothing else left to lose,

00:14:53.960 --> 00:14:56.262
and we ended up with a donut
empire a few years later.

00:14:56.262 --> 00:14:56.970
SPEAKER: Awesome.

00:14:56.970 --> 00:15:01.464
And what made you decide to
do donuts and fried chicken?

00:15:01.464 --> 00:15:04.019
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
[LAUGHS] I don't know.

00:15:04.019 --> 00:15:04.560
But the two--

00:15:04.560 --> 00:15:05.430
SPEAKER: Just sounded good.

00:15:05.430 --> 00:15:06.220
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Yeah,
donut, fried chicken, coffee

00:15:06.220 --> 00:15:08.350
are the three major food
groups in Philadelphia.

00:15:08.350 --> 00:15:13.120
So no, the guys that
we had partnered with

00:15:13.120 --> 00:15:15.660
wanted to do donuts, because
nobody was really doing donuts.

00:15:15.660 --> 00:15:17.710
And I think at the
time, I was just

00:15:17.710 --> 00:15:19.750
eating a shitload of
Korean fried chicken.

00:15:19.750 --> 00:15:22.660
And we were like, we'll have
one piece of equipment, which

00:15:22.660 --> 00:15:25.570
will be a fryer, and we could
do donuts and fried chicken,

00:15:25.570 --> 00:15:27.560
which it turns out
that donuts don't

00:15:27.560 --> 00:15:29.980
taste very good after you've
fried a bunch of chicken

00:15:29.980 --> 00:15:31.630
in them.

00:15:31.630 --> 00:15:34.150
So we bought another
piece of equipment.

00:15:34.150 --> 00:15:34.930
SPEAKER: Got it.

00:15:34.930 --> 00:15:35.430
Got it.

00:15:35.430 --> 00:15:37.180
So how was writing a cookbook?

00:15:37.180 --> 00:15:38.960
What does that
process look like?

00:15:38.960 --> 00:15:42.460
How do you decide, this
is what I want to do?

00:15:42.460 --> 00:15:45.384
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
Well, it is rough.

00:15:45.384 --> 00:15:47.050
Again, this is where
it's very important

00:15:47.050 --> 00:15:50.170
to have an intelligent
business partner that

00:15:50.170 --> 00:15:52.660
can write a cookbook.

00:15:52.660 --> 00:15:55.150
But I think for
the Zahav cookbook,

00:15:55.150 --> 00:15:58.900
it's something that we
wanted to do for years.

00:15:58.900 --> 00:16:02.680
And it took us about
five years to figure out

00:16:02.680 --> 00:16:08.510
what our role was in being this
conduit from Israel to the US,

00:16:08.510 --> 00:16:11.210
or to the Western
market, or whatever.

00:16:11.210 --> 00:16:12.470
Or figure out what our--

00:16:12.470 --> 00:16:15.410
to be comfortable with the role
that we had in Israeli cuisine.

00:16:15.410 --> 00:16:17.270
So it took a long time.

00:16:17.270 --> 00:16:20.890
And there were a lot of moments
where we could have done it

00:16:20.890 --> 00:16:24.630
differently or maybe a little
bit easier, which we didn't do.

00:16:24.630 --> 00:16:25.270
Thank god.

00:16:25.270 --> 00:16:29.320
And my business partner, Steve,
who had never written anything

00:16:29.320 --> 00:16:32.990
professionally ever, after
toying with the idea of ghost

00:16:32.990 --> 00:16:34.430
writers, was like,
I'm just going

00:16:34.430 --> 00:16:37.760
to try to write a head
note, which he did.

00:16:37.760 --> 00:16:39.940
And then he was like, I'm
going to write a chapter.

00:16:39.940 --> 00:16:42.972
And then two years later, he
won two James Beard Awards

00:16:42.972 --> 00:16:44.680
for writing this book,
which was awesome,

00:16:44.680 --> 00:16:47.190
including Book of the Year.

00:16:47.190 --> 00:16:49.250
So Zahav was a
very personal book,

00:16:49.250 --> 00:16:53.470
and it was a book that
the restaurant deserved,

00:16:53.470 --> 00:16:55.950
the movement that we
were a part of deserved.

00:16:55.950 --> 00:16:58.750
And it was something that was
a very-- it's a personal book.

00:16:58.750 --> 00:17:01.570
It's not just an
Israeli cookbook written

00:17:01.570 --> 00:17:05.240
by an Israeli cookbook author.

00:17:05.240 --> 00:17:06.819
It's sort of like
our heart and soul.

00:17:06.819 --> 00:17:09.940
And it's like my family
and this sort of look

00:17:09.940 --> 00:17:14.230
into Israel with your toe
in Israel and in the States.

00:17:14.230 --> 00:17:16.380
The Federal Donuts book
was just kind of fun.

00:17:16.380 --> 00:17:17.410
And we wanted to do it.

00:17:17.410 --> 00:17:19.829
And it's a little bit
silly, and there's

00:17:19.829 --> 00:17:20.950
a workout routine in it.

00:17:20.950 --> 00:17:21.700
SPEAKER: There is.

00:17:21.700 --> 00:17:22.484
I did see it.

00:17:22.484 --> 00:17:24.400
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: I
work out at a boxing gym.

00:17:24.400 --> 00:17:29.900
And my trainer is
part of the cookbook.

00:17:29.900 --> 00:17:31.750
So it's great.

00:17:31.750 --> 00:17:35.210
You do exercises with fried
chicken, squats and stuff.

00:17:35.210 --> 00:17:37.344
And they work.

00:17:37.344 --> 00:17:39.010
And then we're working
on our third book

00:17:39.010 --> 00:17:42.760
right now, which is the next--

00:17:42.760 --> 00:17:44.420
it's like the prequel to Zahav--

00:17:44.420 --> 00:17:45.250
SPEAKER: Very cool.

00:17:45.250 --> 00:17:46.708
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
--which required

00:17:46.708 --> 00:17:49.479
us to be in Israel, shooting
and eating for like 10 days.

00:17:49.479 --> 00:17:50.020
SPEAKER: Wow.

00:17:50.020 --> 00:17:52.730
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: We had 82
meals in, like, eight days.

00:17:52.730 --> 00:17:53.530
AUDIENCE: Wow.

00:17:53.530 --> 00:17:54.195
SPEAKER: Wow.

00:17:54.195 --> 00:17:56.820
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: So we needed
to do a lot of chicken exercise

00:17:56.820 --> 00:17:57.480
after that.

00:17:57.480 --> 00:17:58.160
SPEAKER: I was going to say--

00:17:58.160 --> 00:17:59.260
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
And that is good.

00:17:59.260 --> 00:18:01.150
I'm hoping that we
don't have to do anymore

00:18:01.150 --> 00:18:02.900
cookbooks after this.

00:18:02.900 --> 00:18:03.900
SPEAKER: Three and done.

00:18:03.900 --> 00:18:05.316
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
But it's great.

00:18:05.316 --> 00:18:08.640
It's amazing to
publish something.

00:18:08.640 --> 00:18:11.070
We always thought that
the digital cookbook

00:18:11.070 --> 00:18:12.480
would be the thing.

00:18:12.480 --> 00:18:15.600
There is something about
sitting in your bathrobe,

00:18:15.600 --> 00:18:18.150
reading a cookbook at your
coffee table that is amazing.

00:18:18.150 --> 00:18:21.780
And there is something
about your kids

00:18:21.780 --> 00:18:25.350
seeing it and recognizing
it, and having

00:18:25.350 --> 00:18:29.220
coffee stains, or hummus
stains, or whatever variety

00:18:29.220 --> 00:18:31.530
of food stains that you
have on the cookbook that

00:18:31.530 --> 00:18:33.637
is special and personal.

00:18:33.637 --> 00:18:34.470
SPEAKER: Absolutely.

00:18:34.470 --> 00:18:34.970
Definitely.

00:18:34.970 --> 00:18:37.675
I know I can say I do
like reading my hardcover.

00:18:37.675 --> 00:18:39.550
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: What
kind of food products

00:18:39.550 --> 00:18:41.085
do you have stuck on your book?

00:18:41.085 --> 00:18:43.562
SPEAKER: You know, tea.

00:18:43.562 --> 00:18:44.520
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Tea?

00:18:44.520 --> 00:18:45.480
SPEAKER: On the inside.

00:18:45.480 --> 00:18:46.380
But that's about it.

00:18:46.380 --> 00:18:46.650
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: That's
a really safe answer.

00:18:46.650 --> 00:18:47.040
SPEAKER: I don't know.

00:18:47.040 --> 00:18:49.410
Any other good food products
stuck on your cookbooks

00:18:49.410 --> 00:18:50.100
in the audience?

00:18:50.100 --> 00:18:50.600
Good idea?

00:18:50.600 --> 00:18:51.304
No?

00:18:51.304 --> 00:18:52.090
AUDIENCE: Lemon-garlic paste.

00:18:52.090 --> 00:18:53.430
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Lemon-garlic
paste is a good one.

00:18:53.430 --> 00:18:56.340
SPEAKER: We should do stain
removers for cookbooks.

00:18:56.340 --> 00:18:57.060
Next product.

00:18:57.060 --> 00:18:57.680
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: I don't know.

00:18:57.680 --> 00:19:00.510
Or we should do bookmarks that
are like a piece of steak that

00:19:00.510 --> 00:19:01.980
you just, like--

00:19:01.980 --> 00:19:03.750
SPEAKER: Yes, exactly.

00:19:03.750 --> 00:19:04.710
So you're a busy guy.

00:19:04.710 --> 00:19:08.102
You have multiple restaurants,
multiple cookbooks, traveling.

00:19:08.102 --> 00:19:09.060
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Yes.

00:19:09.060 --> 00:19:10.867
SPEAKER: How do you
keep it all in balance?

00:19:10.867 --> 00:19:12.450
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
I am not the person

00:19:12.450 --> 00:19:13.590
to talk to about balance.

00:19:13.590 --> 00:19:14.670
SPEAKER: OK.

00:19:14.670 --> 00:19:17.700
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: I don't think
that there's ever an ideal.

00:19:17.700 --> 00:19:19.630
I don't think that
there's ever perfect.

00:19:19.630 --> 00:19:22.940
I think that you always
have to prioritize.

00:19:22.940 --> 00:19:26.120
And I think that could be
hour to hour or day to day.

00:19:26.120 --> 00:19:27.680
I don't think looking
too far ahead--

00:19:27.680 --> 00:19:29.060
we write these--

00:19:29.060 --> 00:19:30.920
I have these goals
for the next year.

00:19:30.920 --> 00:19:32.330
And then after
day two, I'm like,

00:19:32.330 --> 00:19:34.360
this is the stupidest
freaking thing ever.

00:19:34.360 --> 00:19:36.170
And it doesn't really
work like that.

00:19:36.170 --> 00:19:39.410
And I think that there's
always short-term and long-term

00:19:39.410 --> 00:19:43.130
happiness, and that these
long-term goals that we have

00:19:43.130 --> 00:19:43.910
are--

00:19:43.910 --> 00:19:46.780
they're important to have,
but they are never accurate.

00:19:46.780 --> 00:19:49.490
And I think they always
should be changing.

00:19:49.490 --> 00:19:50.052
I don't know.

00:19:50.052 --> 00:19:51.260
Not very good about balance--

00:19:51.260 --> 00:19:51.740
SPEAKER: That's OK.

00:19:51.740 --> 00:19:52.550
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: --to
answer your question.

00:19:52.550 --> 00:19:53.550
SPEAKER: We're always
striving here at Google

00:19:53.550 --> 00:19:55.110
to have better balance.

00:19:55.110 --> 00:19:56.030
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: There's
no such thing as perfect,

00:19:56.030 --> 00:19:58.220
yet we're always
trying to achieve it.

00:19:58.220 --> 00:20:04.280
And I think that going
into it and being cognizant

00:20:04.280 --> 00:20:06.530
of the whole thing and being
cognitive about the way

00:20:06.530 --> 00:20:09.960
that you try to attain it
is the most important thing.

00:20:09.960 --> 00:20:10.460
You know?

00:20:10.460 --> 00:20:11.120
SPEAKER: Totally.

00:20:11.120 --> 00:20:11.619
Totally.

00:20:11.619 --> 00:20:12.510
Very cool.

00:20:12.510 --> 00:20:15.180
Well, we'll start opening
up the floor to questions,

00:20:15.180 --> 00:20:17.584
but before we do, I have a
little quick-fire for you.

00:20:17.584 --> 00:20:18.500
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Oh.

00:20:18.500 --> 00:20:20.810
SPEAKER: But you kind of
already answered my first one.

00:20:20.810 --> 00:20:22.580
What is your 2018 New
Year's resolution?

00:20:22.580 --> 00:20:24.329
I know you said you
don't really have one.

00:20:24.329 --> 00:20:25.854
But if you had to pick one.

00:20:25.854 --> 00:20:27.770
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: I
want to drink more water.

00:20:27.770 --> 00:20:28.353
SPEAKER: Cool.

00:20:28.353 --> 00:20:31.970
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: I want to
sleep closer to seven hours

00:20:31.970 --> 00:20:33.840
a night.

00:20:33.840 --> 00:20:38.620
I want to read more
and meditate more.

00:20:38.620 --> 00:20:42.024
I want to land a
backflip on a snowboard.

00:20:42.024 --> 00:20:44.000
SPEAKER: Cool.

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:44.636
Very cool.

00:20:44.636 --> 00:20:45.760
I like-- they're all great.

00:20:45.760 --> 00:20:46.942
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: One of
those things might not happen.

00:20:46.942 --> 00:20:49.154
SPEAKER: I was going
to say, very ambitious.

00:20:49.154 --> 00:20:51.070
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Yeah,
I want to get my kids

00:20:51.070 --> 00:20:53.980
to eat more decent food.

00:20:53.980 --> 00:21:02.160
And we have a couple of
very exciting projects.

00:21:02.160 --> 00:21:05.630
One of them is super
personal, and I really

00:21:05.630 --> 00:21:07.450
want that to open well.

00:21:07.450 --> 00:21:08.220
SPEAKER: Cool.

00:21:08.220 --> 00:21:08.910
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Yeah.

00:21:08.910 --> 00:21:11.000
And how do you pick where
you want to expand to?

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:12.760
I know you have
restaurants in Philly.

00:21:12.760 --> 00:21:14.060
You have restaurants in Miami.

00:21:14.060 --> 00:21:16.852
You have Dizengoff
here in New York.

00:21:16.852 --> 00:21:19.310
What kind of process do you go
through when you're thinking

00:21:19.310 --> 00:21:20.601
about where you want to expand?

00:21:20.601 --> 00:21:22.070
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
Well, I think we

00:21:22.070 --> 00:21:23.480
have these sort of grand plans.

00:21:23.480 --> 00:21:27.230
But I think that a lot
of what we depend on

00:21:27.230 --> 00:21:30.620
is our human resource and
the way that our team grows.

00:21:33.356 --> 00:21:36.380
In hospitality,
you need to accept

00:21:36.380 --> 00:21:39.410
that you are a slave to your
employees, and your team,

00:21:39.410 --> 00:21:41.130
and to your customers.

00:21:41.130 --> 00:21:43.310
And if you don't
find joy in that,

00:21:43.310 --> 00:21:45.350
it's not a good
business to get into.

00:21:45.350 --> 00:21:47.330
And basically, we
just have to listen

00:21:47.330 --> 00:21:50.150
to our customers, and
our guests, and our team,

00:21:50.150 --> 00:21:52.070
and kind of figure out--

00:21:52.070 --> 00:21:55.640
the convergence of
those two relationships

00:21:55.640 --> 00:21:57.170
determines kind of
where we go next.

00:21:57.170 --> 00:21:58.050
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:21:58.050 --> 00:21:59.480
No, I like that.

00:21:59.480 --> 00:22:05.735
So what's your biggest cooking
or kitchen hack, or trick?

00:22:05.735 --> 00:22:08.220
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Trick.

00:22:08.220 --> 00:22:10.623
I mean, I have a lot of tricks.

00:22:10.623 --> 00:22:11.660
SPEAKER: OK, cool.

00:22:11.660 --> 00:22:12.836
What's your favorite?

00:22:12.836 --> 00:22:13.270
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: That's
a very mysterious answer.

00:22:13.270 --> 00:22:14.650
I don't know.

00:22:14.650 --> 00:22:15.420
Be more specific.

00:22:15.420 --> 00:22:18.500
SPEAKER: Is there a way to
cut an onion that no one knows

00:22:18.500 --> 00:22:19.500
that you've figured out?

00:22:19.500 --> 00:22:22.685
Or turning on a
certain temperature

00:22:22.685 --> 00:22:24.000
for a certain sauce?

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:25.470
Like, any hacks
or tricks that you

00:22:25.470 --> 00:22:28.800
could share with the broader,
non-professional chefs?

00:22:28.800 --> 00:22:31.110
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Well, we
refer to this in our book,

00:22:31.110 --> 00:22:36.356
but the secret of our hummus
is very fluffy tehina.

00:22:36.356 --> 00:22:40.260
We blend whole bulbs of
garlic with lemon juice

00:22:40.260 --> 00:22:42.690
and let it sit for,
like, 10 minutes,

00:22:42.690 --> 00:22:44.190
so it mellows the garlic.

00:22:44.190 --> 00:22:47.070
And then pass and
strain the whole thing.

00:22:47.070 --> 00:22:48.370
So it's kind of a step.

00:22:48.370 --> 00:22:50.160
You don't have to peel garlic.

00:22:50.160 --> 00:22:53.220
And the bulb and the skin are
actually pretty delicious.

00:22:53.220 --> 00:22:57.600
We add that to raw tehina and
then whip it with ice water.

00:22:57.600 --> 00:22:59.710
And you end up with
this amazing sauce.

00:22:59.710 --> 00:23:03.780
The other trick is
that when you puree

00:23:03.780 --> 00:23:05.940
whole bulbs of garlic
and lemon juice

00:23:05.940 --> 00:23:09.750
for about 10 seconds, the way
that all the product suspends,

00:23:09.750 --> 00:23:11.520
it looks like a milkshake.

00:23:11.520 --> 00:23:14.790
And if you're working next
to somebody that you dislike,

00:23:14.790 --> 00:23:17.331
you're like, try this
milkshake I made.

00:23:17.331 --> 00:23:18.330
And then they drink it--

00:23:18.330 --> 00:23:20.420
[BLOWS MESSY RASPBERRY] [GROANS]

00:23:20.420 --> 00:23:21.827
SPEAKER: Great hack.

00:23:21.827 --> 00:23:22.410
Perfect trick.

00:23:22.410 --> 00:23:24.659
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: So you
decide which trick you like.

00:23:24.659 --> 00:23:26.410
SPEAKER: [LAUGHS] OK.

00:23:26.410 --> 00:23:28.410
So if you had to pick
one, donuts or hummus?

00:23:31.230 --> 00:23:33.110
[LAUGHS]

00:23:33.110 --> 00:23:34.989
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Cut, cut.

00:23:34.989 --> 00:23:35.530
I don't know.

00:23:35.530 --> 00:23:37.000
They're both fantastic.

00:23:37.000 --> 00:23:37.720
SPEAKER: OK.

00:23:37.720 --> 00:23:39.560
The one food you
can't live without?

00:23:45.180 --> 00:23:49.950
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
I love raw carrots.

00:23:49.950 --> 00:23:52.720
SPEAKER: Nice.

00:23:52.720 --> 00:23:56.680
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: But
I think that legumes are

00:23:56.680 --> 00:24:01.600
pretty delicious and healthy.

00:24:01.600 --> 00:24:05.350
Peanut butter,
have to have that.

00:24:05.350 --> 00:24:07.990
Oh my god, I have to
have peanut butter.

