And god, what is the stop that
has got the great Indo-Paki--

00:27:35.562 --> 00:27:36.270
do you guys know?

00:27:36.270 --> 00:27:36.690
Or what?

00:27:36.690 --> 00:27:36.974
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:27:36.974 --> 00:27:37.971
AUDIENCE: Jackson Heights.

00:27:37.971 --> 00:27:39.845
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Yes,
Jackson Heights, man.

00:27:39.845 --> 00:27:42.100
And then there's
amazing dumplings.

00:27:42.100 --> 00:27:43.787
I mean, it's freaking awesome.

00:27:43.787 --> 00:27:44.370
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:27:44.370 --> 00:27:44.860
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Yeah.

00:27:44.860 --> 00:27:45.790
SPEAKER: Very cool.

00:27:45.790 --> 00:27:46.750
So last question.

00:27:46.750 --> 00:27:49.110
Proudest moment of your career.

00:27:49.110 --> 00:27:50.800
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
That is a good one.

00:27:50.800 --> 00:27:52.340
Do you want to actually hear it?

00:27:52.340 --> 00:27:52.830
SPEAKER: Yeah, let's hear it.

00:27:52.830 --> 00:27:53.746
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: OK.

00:27:53.746 --> 00:27:55.860
So we've won a bunch
of great awards.

00:27:55.860 --> 00:27:59.220
I won the James Beard
Award for Best Chef:

00:27:59.220 --> 00:28:02.910
Mid-Atlantic on Israeli
Independence Day in 2011

00:28:02.910 --> 00:28:06.510
and then Outstanding Chef
again on Independence Day.

00:28:06.510 --> 00:28:09.030
And it was amazing, amazing.

00:28:09.030 --> 00:28:13.302
But I received a letter--

00:28:13.302 --> 00:28:14.010
I'm going to do--

00:28:14.010 --> 00:28:15.307
I'm doing this right now.

00:28:15.307 --> 00:28:16.640
I'm going to read something, OK?

00:28:16.640 --> 00:28:16.870
SPEAKER: Do it.

00:28:16.870 --> 00:28:17.940
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: I've
got to find it on my phone.

00:28:17.940 --> 00:28:19.243
Are you guys ready?

00:28:19.243 --> 00:28:20.050
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:28:20.050 --> 00:28:22.390
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
So here it is.

00:28:22.390 --> 00:28:24.760
"Dear Michael, my
name is Reem, and I'm

00:28:24.760 --> 00:28:29.100
the author of the book you
are holding in your hands."

00:28:29.100 --> 00:28:32.850
And the book was "The
Palestinian Table."

00:28:32.850 --> 00:28:35.490
"I still remember
eating at Zahav

00:28:35.490 --> 00:28:39.810
back in 2008 when I was
a student at Wharton.

00:28:39.810 --> 00:28:44.000
There was a dish of
freekeh topped with chicken

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:47.900
at the time, and I felt so
satisfied and so nostalgic

00:28:47.900 --> 00:28:49.370
when I tasted it."

00:28:49.370 --> 00:28:52.100
And then in parentheses, she
writes, "maybe also a little

00:28:52.100 --> 00:28:53.600
jealous that the
best Arabic food

00:28:53.600 --> 00:28:56.330
I had tasted since
arriving in Philly

00:28:56.330 --> 00:28:58.100
was at an Israeli restaurant."

00:28:58.100 --> 00:29:01.299
And then she did the
"semi-colon smile" thing,

00:29:01.299 --> 00:29:03.090
which is weird when
somebody writes it out.

00:29:03.090 --> 00:29:04.771
But I liked it.

00:29:04.771 --> 00:29:07.377
[LAUGHTER]

00:29:07.377 --> 00:29:08.960
Because Palestinian
and Israeli, we're

00:29:08.960 --> 00:29:10.970
all insecure line cooks
at the end of the day.

00:29:10.970 --> 00:29:12.420
And I was like, yeah, we won.

00:29:12.420 --> 00:29:15.365
So, "It's been almost
a decade since,

00:29:15.365 --> 00:29:17.900
and I just moved back to Philly
with my family from London

00:29:17.900 --> 00:29:19.010
this past year.

00:29:19.010 --> 00:29:22.260
It's amazing to see what you've
done since I was here last.

00:29:22.260 --> 00:29:24.260
To be honest, I wanted
to reach out for a while,

00:29:24.260 --> 00:29:25.940
but I hesitated.

00:29:25.940 --> 00:29:28.522
Yet when I watched 'In Search
of Israeli Cuisine,'" which was

00:29:28.522 --> 00:29:30.800
a documentary I was
in, "this past week,

00:29:30.800 --> 00:29:35.000
I realized what a genuine,
fun, curious person you are.

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:37.340
And it reaffirmed my
desire to reach out to you

00:29:37.340 --> 00:29:38.790
and get to know you.

00:29:38.790 --> 00:29:41.960
I believe food can help
start a conversation where

00:29:41.960 --> 00:29:43.720
nothing else has been able to.

00:29:43.720 --> 00:29:45.991
And I hope my book is a
testament to that fact.

00:29:45.991 --> 00:29:47.990
As it happens, the
photographer who shot my book

00:29:47.990 --> 00:29:51.532
is Israeli, Dan Perez.

00:29:51.532 --> 00:29:53.240
And the whole process
of working together

00:29:53.240 --> 00:29:55.550
reaffirmed to me how the
human spirit can rise

00:29:55.550 --> 00:29:58.370
above our muddled politics.

00:29:58.370 --> 00:30:03.460
So I just wanted to
share my book with you

00:30:03.460 --> 00:30:05.969
and say thank you for the
inspiration you've been.

00:30:05.969 --> 00:30:07.510
You certainly don't
need my cookbook,

00:30:07.510 --> 00:30:09.940
but I do hope you enjoy
looking through it

00:30:09.940 --> 00:30:13.080
and maybe find a small piece
of our shared home inside it.

00:30:13.080 --> 00:30:15.580
Until we meet in person, I leave
you with my warmest wishes.

00:30:15.580 --> 00:30:16.461
Reem."

00:30:16.461 --> 00:30:16.960
Yeah.

00:30:16.960 --> 00:30:17.530
SPEAKER: That's pretty amazing.

00:30:17.530 --> 00:30:18.620
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: That was
the best part of my career.

00:30:18.620 --> 00:30:18.850
SPEAKER: Wow.

00:30:18.850 --> 00:30:19.320
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Yup.

00:30:19.320 --> 00:30:20.254
[APPLAUSE]

00:30:20.254 --> 00:30:22.860
SPEAKER: Applause for that.

00:30:22.860 --> 00:30:23.720
Amazing.

00:30:23.720 --> 00:30:25.840
And now you have
it on your phone

00:30:25.840 --> 00:30:26.980
and you can always find it.

00:30:26.980 --> 00:30:28.980
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Or I
can struggle to find it.

00:30:28.980 --> 00:30:30.160
But it's there.

00:30:30.160 --> 00:30:31.660
Yeah, I think that
that is the best.

00:30:31.660 --> 00:30:34.180
I think that that is by far
the most important thing.

00:30:34.180 --> 00:30:38.470
And we have goals in
2018, which may or may not

00:30:38.470 --> 00:30:40.890
be harder than landing a
backflip on a snowboard,

00:30:40.890 --> 00:30:41.689
but we'll see.

00:30:41.689 --> 00:30:42.480
SPEAKER: Who knows.

00:30:42.480 --> 00:30:43.180
TBD.

00:30:43.180 --> 00:30:43.840
That's awesome.

00:30:43.840 --> 00:30:44.260
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Thanks.

