should be really pliable,
so you can scoop and wipe,

00:32:21.660 --> 00:32:24.420
and also needs to
hold up, so you

00:32:24.420 --> 00:32:28.460
can make a sandwich with it,
drive a car, talk on the phone,

00:32:28.460 --> 00:32:32.610
and smoke a cigarette
at the same time, which

00:32:32.610 --> 00:32:34.273
is the test of a perfect pita.

00:32:34.273 --> 00:32:35.040
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:32:35.040 --> 00:32:35.830
I will test for that.

00:32:35.830 --> 00:32:38.121
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: In the
book, we have a great recipe.

00:32:38.121 --> 00:32:40.560
AUDIENCE: With trends like
Yelp, Instagram, and podcasts,

00:32:40.560 --> 00:32:42.060
what are some of
the pros and cons

00:32:42.060 --> 00:32:45.247
that you see in these,
as a restaurant owner?

00:32:45.247 --> 00:32:47.580
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: I think
that every industry is always

00:32:47.580 --> 00:32:48.050
changing.

00:32:48.050 --> 00:32:50.508
I think the restaurant industry
is definitely no exception.

00:32:50.508 --> 00:32:54.170
And I think that people
hate on Yelp, for example.

00:32:54.170 --> 00:32:55.920
And everyone-- it's
like, ooh, Yelpers.

00:32:55.920 --> 00:32:58.650
But I mean, if I go
to a table at Zahav,

00:32:58.650 --> 00:33:01.530
and I'm like, hey, covered in
flour, bringing the pita over,

00:33:01.530 --> 00:33:03.120
and I'm like, what do you think?

00:33:03.120 --> 00:33:05.120
You're going to be like,
oh, my god, it's great.

00:33:05.120 --> 00:33:05.910
Thank you so much.

00:33:05.910 --> 00:33:06.870
And then you're going to
leave and you're going

00:33:06.870 --> 00:33:08.130
to be like, that place sucks.

00:33:08.130 --> 00:33:09.050
You know?

00:33:09.050 --> 00:33:13.320
And the good thing about Yelp
is even though sometimes I

00:33:13.320 --> 00:33:17.310
lose sleep over
how brutally honest

00:33:17.310 --> 00:33:21.120
it can be, it's one of the
only ways to get real feedback.

00:33:21.120 --> 00:33:24.900
So a lot of people hate on Yelp.

00:33:24.900 --> 00:33:26.250
The truth is we read--

00:33:26.250 --> 00:33:30.570
I read-- everybody in my
company reads our Yelp reviews

00:33:30.570 --> 00:33:31.810
every single day.

00:33:31.810 --> 00:33:34.230
And we respond to every
single one of them.

00:33:34.230 --> 00:33:35.980
And we take them
all very seriously.

00:33:35.980 --> 00:33:39.160
So it's annoying when--

00:33:39.160 --> 00:33:42.190
it's annoying, because I want
people to like everything

00:33:42.190 --> 00:33:43.720
that I do.

00:33:43.720 --> 00:33:46.120
The reality is we're in the
most subjective industry,

00:33:46.120 --> 00:33:49.300
and we're trying to
please, I don't know,

00:33:49.300 --> 00:33:52.790
like thousands of people a week
that all have different taste

00:33:52.790 --> 00:33:53.440
buds.

00:33:53.440 --> 00:33:56.154
And there's no real
way to do that.

00:33:56.154 --> 00:33:57.070
But the other things--

00:33:57.070 --> 00:34:01.510
I mean, it's just a function of
what it is that we do, right?

00:34:01.510 --> 00:34:04.000
The industry and
environment that you're in

00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:07.900
is only about
progressive ingenuity.

00:34:07.900 --> 00:34:09.790
And I think restaurants
are exactly the same.

00:34:09.790 --> 00:34:11.800
And trends are happening
now because people

00:34:11.800 --> 00:34:13.330
are interested in food.

00:34:13.330 --> 00:34:17.469
And media and communications
are just out there.

00:34:17.469 --> 00:34:24.232
And having an Instagram account
with thousands of followers

00:34:24.232 --> 00:34:26.190
coming to the restaurant,
and taking a picture,

00:34:26.190 --> 00:34:29.940
and posting it is sometimes
just as important as a review

00:34:29.940 --> 00:34:34.659
from a critic, which
is crazy a little bit.

00:34:34.659 --> 00:34:36.670
But it's just the way it goes.

00:34:36.670 --> 00:34:38.417
So I think that it's
kind of exciting.

00:34:38.417 --> 00:34:40.500
I can't wait to see what's
next and the way that--

00:34:43.289 --> 00:34:43.830
I don't know.

00:34:43.830 --> 00:34:45.929
There's a lot of things
happening at the same time

00:34:45.929 --> 00:34:46.429
right now.

00:34:46.429 --> 00:34:50.550
We've got environment,
labor, all these sort

00:34:50.550 --> 00:34:51.750
of topics and issues.

00:34:51.750 --> 00:34:54.929
And the way that technology
and ingenuity, I think,

00:34:54.929 --> 00:34:57.240
are going to help put things
in the right direction.

00:34:57.240 --> 00:35:00.630
And to be part of it in one way
or another is pretty exciting.

00:35:00.630 --> 00:35:01.660
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:35:01.660 --> 00:35:02.662
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Yeah.

00:35:02.662 --> 00:35:04.620
AUDIENCE: I watched the
documentary on Netflix,

00:35:04.620 --> 00:35:06.745
and my husband and I were
grinning from ear to ear,

00:35:06.745 --> 00:35:07.807
because it was so great.

00:35:07.807 --> 00:35:08.890
You guys have to watch it.

00:35:08.890 --> 00:35:10.720
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Thank you.

00:35:10.720 --> 00:35:12.160
AUDIENCE: Question, though.

00:35:12.160 --> 00:35:15.710
We noticed that falafel
wasn't really mentioned.

00:35:15.710 --> 00:35:18.460
And it's such an
iconic food of Israel

00:35:18.460 --> 00:35:20.500
and that region of
the Middle East.

00:35:20.500 --> 00:35:24.310
So I'm curious if there was a
specific reason it was omitted

00:35:24.310 --> 00:35:27.220
or you guys just had so many
other good subjects it couldn't

00:35:27.220 --> 00:35:27.720
be included.

00:35:27.720 --> 00:35:29.050
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Yeah, I
mean, come to think of it,

00:35:29.050 --> 00:35:29.924
I guess you're right.

00:35:29.924 --> 00:35:31.480
We ate so much falafel.

00:35:34.120 --> 00:35:34.900
I just don't know.

00:35:34.900 --> 00:35:36.790
I don't actually know.

00:35:36.790 --> 00:35:40.360
The filmmaker Roger
Sherman would probably

00:35:40.360 --> 00:35:41.890
answer that better.

00:35:41.890 --> 00:35:43.880
But I don't think
there was a reason.

00:35:43.880 --> 00:35:45.255
I don't think we
were like, well,

00:35:45.255 --> 00:35:47.689
we can't do falafel,
because that's too much--

00:35:47.689 --> 00:35:48.730
SPEAKER: Too [INAUDIBLE].

00:35:48.730 --> 00:35:49.480
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
--too much or whatever.

00:35:49.480 --> 00:35:49.850
AUDIENCE: Too controversial.

00:35:49.850 --> 00:35:50.629
SPEAKER: [LAUGHS]

00:35:50.629 --> 00:35:52.420
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: What
you saw on the film

00:35:52.420 --> 00:35:54.340
was like 20% of what we shot.

00:35:54.340 --> 00:35:57.140
And we were there for
three and a half weeks,

00:35:57.140 --> 00:35:59.710
eating seven times a day.

00:35:59.710 --> 00:36:02.050
It was crazy.

00:36:02.050 --> 00:36:05.980
So I don't know why there
wasn't a falafel documentary.

00:36:05.980 --> 00:36:07.349
There should be.

00:36:07.349 --> 00:36:07.890
Only falafel.

00:36:07.890 --> 00:36:09.849
AUDIENCE: Is there enough
footage for a Part 2?

00:36:09.849 --> 00:36:12.056
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: There
could be footage for Part 2.

00:36:12.056 --> 00:36:13.410
I mean, it could go on forever.

00:36:13.410 --> 00:36:17.090
And what's funny is that we
shot that five years ago.

00:36:17.090 --> 00:36:19.000
I go to Israel at
least once a year.

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:24.030
I obviously go to visit family.

00:36:24.030 --> 00:36:25.620
But it's like my job.

00:36:25.620 --> 00:36:27.540
I eat all the time.

00:36:27.540 --> 00:36:29.700
And most of the places
that we went to I

00:36:29.700 --> 00:36:31.820
had not even heard of.

00:36:31.820 --> 00:36:35.000
And a lot of places that I
go back to, I don't even--

00:36:35.000 --> 00:36:36.750
the country is the
size of New Jersey.

00:36:36.750 --> 00:36:40.580
And it's just like you could
not skip a meal or a cuisine

00:36:40.580 --> 00:36:41.750
for weeks.

00:36:41.750 --> 00:36:44.812
It's just so
gastronomically rich.

00:36:44.812 --> 00:36:47.270
But I think that was kind of
the point that we were making.

00:36:47.270 --> 00:36:48.978
But I don't know about
the falafel thing.

00:36:48.978 --> 00:36:51.858
We should definitely
make a complaint on Yelp

00:36:51.858 --> 00:36:53.172
to the filmmaker.

00:36:53.172 --> 00:36:54.700
AUDIENCE: It was still great.

00:36:54.700 --> 00:36:55.270
Thank you.

00:36:55.270 --> 00:36:56.710
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Thank you.

00:36:56.710 --> 00:36:58.370
If you're a falafel fan too,
you should come to Philly.

00:36:58.370 --> 00:36:59.750
We have a good
falafel shop there.

00:36:59.750 --> 00:37:00.374
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:37:00.374 --> 00:37:02.909
We've actually been talking
about taking a little day trip.

00:37:02.909 --> 00:37:03.950
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Do it.

00:37:03.950 --> 00:37:09.500
Get the Google bus, or airplane,
or helicopters, and come down.

00:37:09.500 --> 00:37:11.490
Yeah, the copter.

00:37:11.490 --> 00:37:13.990
AUDIENCE: So first of all, thank
you so much for being here.

00:37:13.990 --> 00:37:14.620
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
Thanks for having me.

00:37:14.620 --> 00:37:16.203
AUDIENCE: My mom is
Israeli, actually,

00:37:16.203 --> 00:37:18.910
and I definitely connected
with the kind of eclectic food

00:37:18.910 --> 00:37:21.460
that I grew up eating,
like from hummus,

00:37:21.460 --> 00:37:23.345
obviously, to
schnitzel, to borscht,

00:37:23.345 --> 00:37:26.110
to blintzes, to you name
it, by the way of Poland,

00:37:26.110 --> 00:37:27.460
I should say.

00:37:27.460 --> 00:37:29.890
So obviously, Dizengoff is
kind of a different kind

00:37:29.890 --> 00:37:31.450
of hospitality than Zahav.

00:37:31.450 --> 00:37:33.684
It's more of a
takeout spot for me.

00:37:33.684 --> 00:37:36.100
I'm curious what you think
just in terms of the restaurant

00:37:36.100 --> 00:37:37.810
industry about delivery?

00:37:37.810 --> 00:37:40.282
Do you think delivery
is the next great thing?

00:37:40.282 --> 00:37:41.740
Do you think it's
a necessary evil?

00:37:41.740 --> 00:37:44.902
Do you think it's kind of
the downfall of restaurants?

00:37:44.902 --> 00:37:46.360
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
And we were sort

00:37:46.360 --> 00:37:47.484
of touching on this before.

00:37:47.484 --> 00:37:49.060
I definitely think
it's the future.

00:37:49.060 --> 00:37:52.630
I think that takeout--

00:37:52.630 --> 00:37:54.790
I mean, especially in
metropolitan areas,

00:37:54.790 --> 00:37:57.442
are the way that we
sort of work, I guess.

00:37:57.442 --> 00:37:59.650
I think that delivery makes
the most amount of sense.

00:37:59.650 --> 00:38:01.920
And I think figuring out
the way to do that is

00:38:01.920 --> 00:38:03.110
sort of the next big thing.

00:38:03.110 --> 00:38:07.547
And for us-- and this
goes back to the reason

00:38:07.547 --> 00:38:08.630
that we cook Israeli food.

00:38:08.630 --> 00:38:10.730
It's my food memories,
the reasons that I cook,

00:38:10.730 --> 00:38:12.530
are not because
of a seven-course

00:38:12.530 --> 00:38:15.220
or 12-course tasting menu
at a Michelin restaurant.

00:38:15.220 --> 00:38:17.820
It's about having the perfect
pita and hummus that make

00:38:17.820 --> 00:38:21.220
me want to explode with joy.

00:38:21.220 --> 00:38:24.200
And I think that you have
that opportunity with takeout,

00:38:24.200 --> 00:38:27.170
with fast casual.

00:38:27.170 --> 00:38:28.110
And it definitely is.

00:38:28.110 --> 00:38:31.330
And I think, actually, a lot of
places are doing it quite well.

00:38:31.330 --> 00:38:35.010
I think there still is
a lot of room for that--

00:38:35.010 --> 00:38:38.555
the Dizengoff partnership
here with you all could work.

00:38:38.555 --> 00:38:40.680
But I think that that is
definitely the next thing.

00:38:40.680 --> 00:38:42.638
AUDIENCE: I guess to
maybe be more specifically

00:38:42.638 --> 00:38:44.310
around the actual
kind of texture,

00:38:44.310 --> 00:38:46.110
flavor, heat, temperature,
all those things

00:38:46.110 --> 00:38:47.980
around the perfect
pita, for example--

00:38:47.980 --> 00:38:50.100
how that travels and some of the
challenges that go with that.

00:38:50.100 --> 00:38:50.820
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: I know.

00:38:50.820 --> 00:38:52.210
We're working on that too.

00:38:52.210 --> 00:38:55.860
And I think that the
perfect pita, for us,

00:38:55.860 --> 00:38:57.510
goes in Styrofoam, sealed.

00:38:57.510 --> 00:38:59.960
So we're waiting for somebody--

00:38:59.960 --> 00:39:01.590
and maybe in your
free time, guys,

00:39:01.590 --> 00:39:03.340
you can start working on this.

00:39:03.340 --> 00:39:08.850
There are people using
fungus, actually,

00:39:08.850 --> 00:39:15.150
sort of like plastic-esque
fungus that sort of simulates

00:39:15.150 --> 00:39:17.250
airtight plastic.

00:39:17.250 --> 00:39:19.912
So we need that, because that
is what the perfect pita is.

00:39:19.912 --> 00:39:21.120
It is soft, and it is fluffy.

00:39:21.120 --> 00:39:23.340
And it doesn't even
have to be warm.

00:39:23.340 --> 00:39:24.540
But sealing it is good.

00:39:24.540 --> 00:39:25.470
And we do that now.

00:39:25.470 --> 00:39:26.970
When we dropped
off pita here, we

00:39:26.970 --> 00:39:28.845
brought over these giant
Styrofoam containers

00:39:28.845 --> 00:39:29.960
that we reuse.

00:39:29.960 --> 00:39:35.400
But as much as I think it would
make a great Instagram video,

00:39:35.400 --> 00:39:38.770
we can't drop off one pita with
a giant Styrofoam container,

00:39:38.770 --> 00:39:40.260
and open it up.

00:39:40.260 --> 00:39:41.280
You know?

00:39:41.280 --> 00:39:43.690
What we should do is put a
human being inside of it,

00:39:43.690 --> 00:39:46.010
so when you open it up, they
jump out and they're like,

00:39:46.010 --> 00:39:48.450
here's your pita,
and they run away.

00:39:48.450 --> 00:39:53.000
So that's what we're
going to work on next.

00:39:53.000 --> 00:39:54.820
I do think it's kind
of the next big thing.

00:39:54.820 --> 00:39:57.580
But I think that goes
for every type of food.

00:39:57.580 --> 00:40:00.480
There's so many different
kinds of iconic street food

00:40:00.480 --> 00:40:03.810
that people are used to eating
in the street and standing up.

00:40:03.810 --> 00:40:06.230
And delivery of it
kind of messes it up.

00:40:06.230 --> 00:40:07.120
So yeah.

00:40:10.585 --> 00:40:12.070
Hey.

00:40:12.070 --> 00:40:13.070
AUDIENCE: Hello?

00:40:13.070 --> 00:40:15.050
You briefly mentioned
your business partner.

00:40:15.050 --> 00:40:17.540
I think his name was
Steve, and how important it

00:40:17.540 --> 00:40:18.620
was to have a good one.

00:40:18.620 --> 00:40:19.760
It makes perfect sense.

00:40:19.760 --> 00:40:20.150
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Yes.

00:40:20.150 --> 00:40:21.608
AUDIENCE: Can you
talk a little bit

00:40:21.608 --> 00:40:24.950
about how you guys
came to work together,

00:40:24.950 --> 00:40:27.510
where you experienced the most
friction with one another,

00:40:27.510 --> 00:40:31.375
and how you make decisions
when you inevitably disagree?

00:40:31.375 --> 00:40:33.250
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Those
are great questions.

00:40:33.250 --> 00:40:36.040
And those are things that we,
after being in business for 10

00:40:36.040 --> 00:40:39.295
years, becoming best friends
after being business partners,

00:40:39.295 --> 00:40:41.174
you always have to re-examine.

00:40:41.174 --> 00:40:43.090
And sometimes they can
be super uncomfortable.

00:40:43.090 --> 00:40:46.480
And we're opposite
people, which I

00:40:46.480 --> 00:40:50.860
think makes a better product
for our guests and for our team.

00:40:50.860 --> 00:40:58.840
He was an investment banker
that hated it from day one.

00:40:58.840 --> 00:41:03.820
He was here, working for
Blackstone in the late '90s,

00:41:03.820 --> 00:41:07.360
then decided to go to
culinary school at night,

00:41:07.360 --> 00:41:10.510
and then opened a
restaurant in Philadelphia,

00:41:10.510 --> 00:41:13.540
and then after a short period
of time, got really burned out.

00:41:13.540 --> 00:41:17.170
And his wife and I grew
up together in Pittsburgh.

00:41:17.170 --> 00:41:22.390
So we met and hung out, and
then started opening restaurants

00:41:22.390 --> 00:41:22.960
together.

00:41:22.960 --> 00:41:32.170
And I think that the way that
we contradict one another,

00:41:32.170 --> 00:41:34.580
it forces a conversation.

00:41:34.580 --> 00:41:37.510
And I think that we
ultimately take ourselves

00:41:37.510 --> 00:41:39.340
out of the equation,
because you have

00:41:39.340 --> 00:41:43.000
to change the narrative if
it's like the two of you that

00:41:43.000 --> 00:41:45.760
have everything that you've
ever worked on or invested--

00:41:45.760 --> 00:41:50.260
you know, we invest everything
together all the time.

00:41:50.260 --> 00:41:51.670
So we have to make
decisions that

00:41:51.670 --> 00:41:54.520
are super subjective
but also very objective,

00:41:54.520 --> 00:41:56.970
because we're
considering so much.

00:41:56.970 --> 00:42:00.460
And I think the back-and-forth
friction is actually

00:42:00.460 --> 00:42:01.060
a good thing.

00:42:08.270 --> 00:42:10.730
We have to adjust,
basically, and we

00:42:10.730 --> 00:42:13.190
have to remember that
we're not the only people

00:42:13.190 --> 00:42:15.080
making decisions all the time.

00:42:15.080 --> 00:42:18.290
And sometimes they
can be dragged out,

00:42:18.290 --> 00:42:20.500
and sometimes they can
be funny and ironic,

00:42:20.500 --> 00:42:22.100
and then sometimes
they can breed

00:42:22.100 --> 00:42:24.200
probably a very low
level of resentment

00:42:24.200 --> 00:42:27.690
until we talk it out.

00:42:27.690 --> 00:42:33.710
But I think that we're always
consciously disagreeing

00:42:33.710 --> 00:42:35.000
on things.

00:42:35.000 --> 00:42:36.620
And I feel like that ends up--

00:42:40.202 --> 00:42:43.290
we sort of always have
our eye on the prize.

00:42:43.290 --> 00:42:44.020
I don't like it.

00:42:44.020 --> 00:42:46.380
I don't like confrontation.

00:42:46.380 --> 00:42:50.300
And I am really animated.

00:42:50.300 --> 00:42:53.320
And when I get pissed off,
I yell and throw things.

00:42:53.320 --> 00:42:56.810
And he is very quiet
and will stare at you

00:42:56.810 --> 00:42:59.340
for an hour and a half
until he gets what he wants.

00:43:01.850 --> 00:43:04.450
And he's also super intelligent.

00:43:04.450 --> 00:43:09.210
And I am what I like to call
emotionally intelligent.

00:43:13.700 --> 00:43:15.260
I think that we're
sort of forced

00:43:15.260 --> 00:43:18.250
to come up with decisions
together because of that.

00:43:18.250 --> 00:43:22.040
And when you have everything
collateralized for bank loans,

00:43:22.040 --> 00:43:24.690
you can't just walk away.

00:43:24.690 --> 00:43:28.960
And I think that
also, what's been

00:43:28.960 --> 00:43:32.260
really funny is, because of
the nature of our industry,

00:43:32.260 --> 00:43:35.064
people see me as the guy
that does everything.

00:43:35.064 --> 00:43:36.730
Because people like
chefs, because we're

00:43:36.730 --> 00:43:41.050
on TV, because we have tattoos,
and because we drop F bombs.

00:43:41.050 --> 00:43:43.620
And people love that, and
they think we're creative.

00:43:43.620 --> 00:43:46.210
The reality is everything
that I've ever done

00:43:46.210 --> 00:43:47.530
has been with Steve.

00:43:47.530 --> 00:43:49.960
Like a lot of our
restaurants-- because I

00:43:49.960 --> 00:43:52.270
tend to work at Zahav a lot.

00:43:52.270 --> 00:43:54.100
We have 14 restaurants.

00:43:54.100 --> 00:43:55.970
I don't make decisions
for all of them.

00:43:55.970 --> 00:43:57.576
He's got a finance background.

00:43:57.576 --> 00:43:59.450
Obviously, when we're
writing business plans,

00:43:59.450 --> 00:44:05.005
I'm not the guy that's
like, fuckin' whatever.

00:44:05.005 --> 00:44:07.524
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:08.650 --> 00:44:13.670
Loan officers don't love
that sort of discussion.

00:44:13.670 --> 00:44:18.050
So a lot of what we've had
to do is check our egos.

00:44:18.050 --> 00:44:19.970
And every time an
article gets published

00:44:19.970 --> 00:44:22.960
that's like Michael
Solomonov's restaurant empire,

00:44:22.960 --> 00:44:25.610
I get offended by it.

00:44:25.610 --> 00:44:27.910
And I need to sit and
be like, Steve, I'm

00:44:27.910 --> 00:44:32.800
so sorry that that has
happened, because it's bullshit,

00:44:32.800 --> 00:44:36.500
because we have 250
people that work for us.

00:44:36.500 --> 00:44:38.500
Steve and I come
up with everything.

00:44:38.500 --> 00:44:42.610
Steve has written three books.

00:44:42.610 --> 00:44:44.350
One of them won
two Beard Awards,

00:44:44.350 --> 00:44:46.810
including Book of the Year.

00:44:46.810 --> 00:44:49.140
And people still look
at my name as the thing.

00:44:49.140 --> 00:44:53.080
So a lot of it has to be that
emotional sort of checking.

00:44:53.080 --> 00:44:56.680
And in the office,
people go to Steve

00:44:56.680 --> 00:44:59.300
and want him to make decisions.

00:44:59.300 --> 00:45:01.480
And I'm like, hey, dude,
I'm like a 50% owner

00:45:01.480 --> 00:45:03.220
of all these things.

00:45:03.220 --> 00:45:05.380
And although I
get lippy and loud

00:45:05.380 --> 00:45:07.410
and don't have
business experience,

00:45:07.410 --> 00:45:08.500
we've built this together.

00:45:08.500 --> 00:45:10.780
So on one hand,
my ego gets hurt.

00:45:10.780 --> 00:45:12.460
On the other hand,
his gets hurt.

00:45:12.460 --> 00:45:15.430
And we have to sit
and do kumbaya often,

00:45:15.430 --> 00:45:18.670
or trust falls with one another,
which are not effective.

00:45:18.670 --> 00:45:20.050
You need more than two people.

00:45:24.400 --> 00:45:25.450
I think it's awesome.

00:45:25.450 --> 00:45:29.900
And I think that he's, for
all intents and purposes,

00:45:29.900 --> 00:45:30.710
like my brother.

00:45:30.710 --> 00:45:35.870
And we've been to hell and
back and through hell and back

00:45:35.870 --> 00:45:36.470
together.

00:45:36.470 --> 00:45:40.640
And I love the idea of what--

00:45:40.640 --> 00:45:43.530
we've been partners
together for like a decade

00:45:43.530 --> 00:45:44.760
and built so much together.

00:45:44.760 --> 00:45:48.080
And I think a lot of that
has to do with our resilience

00:45:48.080 --> 00:45:49.370
as a team.

00:45:49.370 --> 00:45:50.044
So it's good.

00:45:50.044 --> 00:45:51.710
But it's hard to work
with other people.

00:45:51.710 --> 00:45:52.910
It is not easy.

00:45:52.910 --> 00:45:54.710
Most relationships fall apart.

00:45:54.710 --> 00:45:55.940
Most egos fall apart.

00:45:55.940 --> 00:45:58.730
And the moment you start
believing everything positive

00:45:58.730 --> 00:46:00.600
written about you
and take it to heart

00:46:00.600 --> 00:46:03.670
is when things do fall apart.

00:46:03.670 --> 00:46:06.674
So don't get into the restaurant
business is what I'm saying.

00:46:06.674 --> 00:46:08.090
Thanks for your
questions, though.

00:46:08.090 --> 00:46:10.230
They were really-- I
hope I answered them.

00:46:10.230 --> 00:46:10.730
Hey.

00:46:10.730 --> 00:46:12.820
AUDIENCE: Hi, I have a
lighthearted question.

00:46:12.820 --> 00:46:15.890
You mentioned one of your
New Year's resolutions

00:46:15.890 --> 00:46:17.400
was to have your
kids eat better.

00:46:17.400 --> 00:46:18.400
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Yeah.

00:46:18.400 --> 00:46:20.360
AUDIENCE: As a new mom
of a young daughter,

00:46:20.360 --> 00:46:22.100
I'm just curious--
like, real talk,

00:46:22.100 --> 00:46:24.980
I'm guessing your kids
don't eat dino chicken

00:46:24.980 --> 00:46:26.780
nuggets on a random Tuesday.

00:46:26.780 --> 00:46:27.590
Maybe they do.

00:46:27.590 --> 00:46:28.829
But what is the before?

00:46:28.829 --> 00:46:29.870
What are they eating now?

00:46:29.870 --> 00:46:32.330
What do you hope
they would eat later?

00:46:32.330 --> 00:46:33.110
I'm just curious.

00:46:33.110 --> 00:46:34.917
What's the before and
after in your world?

00:46:34.917 --> 00:46:36.500
I'm guessing it's
different than mine.

00:46:36.500 --> 00:46:38.041
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
It always changes.

00:46:38.041 --> 00:46:40.590
And I think the one constant
is that there is no absolute

00:46:40.590 --> 00:46:42.020
and that whenever
you think you're

00:46:42.020 --> 00:46:44.970
onto some thing with your
kid, it always changes.

00:46:44.970 --> 00:46:47.250
So the things that
they've always enjoyed,

00:46:47.250 --> 00:46:51.440
though, have been Asian
noodle soup, which I'm lucky,

00:46:51.440 --> 00:46:54.520
because we can do pho.

00:46:54.520 --> 00:46:56.320
We can do ramen,
that kind of thing.

00:46:56.320 --> 00:46:59.950
Greens and herbs and stuff
are a little bit tricky.

00:46:59.950 --> 00:47:02.860
But I think that
bribing them with candy

00:47:02.860 --> 00:47:04.690
is what you should do.

00:47:04.690 --> 00:47:07.300
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:07.300 --> 00:47:09.400
And I'm also not above--

00:47:09.400 --> 00:47:11.110
I get a little--

00:47:11.110 --> 00:47:13.900
I fly off the handle
and will sometimes

00:47:13.900 --> 00:47:17.530
border on being a crazy parent.

00:47:17.530 --> 00:47:20.740
And like a little pat on
the back, grab on the neck,

00:47:20.740 --> 00:47:23.360
and I'm like, you're
going to eat this.

00:47:23.360 --> 00:47:25.570
But I think it's
always a victory.

00:47:25.570 --> 00:47:28.030
My oldest son will not eat
a peanut butter and jelly

00:47:28.030 --> 00:47:32.745
sandwich, but will eat head-on,
shell-on shrimp tail first.

00:47:32.745 --> 00:47:34.120
And I'm like,
dude, you're eating

00:47:34.120 --> 00:47:37.830
Szechuan shrimp that are so
spicy, no adult will eat that.

00:47:37.830 --> 00:47:40.720
But why won't you
eat Wonder Bread?

00:47:40.720 --> 00:47:43.630
And I think what you have to
do is celebrate the shrimp

00:47:43.630 --> 00:47:46.570
and then find shrimp all
over the city to go eat.

00:47:46.570 --> 00:47:47.640
And then you do it.

00:47:47.640 --> 00:47:49.900
But bribing with candy is
definitely the only way

00:47:49.900 --> 00:47:52.270
to actually make it work.

00:47:52.270 --> 00:47:54.610
And M&amp;M's have these
caramel ones right

00:47:54.610 --> 00:47:55.610
now that the kids love.

00:47:55.610 --> 00:47:57.817
And that will get them--
they'll eat anything.

00:47:57.817 --> 00:47:59.650
SPEAKER: Do you cook
at home a lot for them?

00:47:59.650 --> 00:48:01.441
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: That
is the other thing.

00:48:01.441 --> 00:48:04.870
I think having them
participate is a huge thing

00:48:04.870 --> 00:48:05.800
and being part of it.

00:48:05.800 --> 00:48:09.160
And even baby fingers
picking cilantro

00:48:09.160 --> 00:48:12.310
leaves that they will
never eat, still exciting,

00:48:12.310 --> 00:48:14.320
and they're still
part of that, too.

00:48:14.320 --> 00:48:17.620
But I've found smoothies,
you can do a lot.

00:48:17.620 --> 00:48:20.761
If you start with a banana
and strawberry, you can--

00:48:20.761 --> 00:48:21.760
AUDIENCE: Throw in kale.

00:48:21.760 --> 00:48:22.570
Throw in whatever.

00:48:22.570 --> 00:48:24.695
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Or like
eye of newt or whatever.

00:48:24.695 --> 00:48:26.380
You can put anything in there.

00:48:26.380 --> 00:48:28.420
As long as it's red and
smells like a banana,

00:48:28.420 --> 00:48:31.322
you could put anything in there.

00:48:31.322 --> 00:48:32.155
AUDIENCE: It's true.

00:48:32.155 --> 00:48:32.410
Yeah.

00:48:32.410 --> 00:48:34.326
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Like,
gravel if you wanted.

00:48:34.326 --> 00:48:37.581
It wouldn't make a difference.

00:48:37.581 --> 00:48:38.080
Any other--

00:48:38.080 --> 00:48:38.395
SPEAKER: Good to know.

00:48:38.395 --> 00:48:40.054
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV:
Any other questions?

00:48:40.054 --> 00:48:40.970
SPEAKER: Good to know.

00:48:40.970 --> 00:48:41.340
Oh.

00:48:41.340 --> 00:48:42.256
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: Oh.

00:48:42.256 --> 00:48:44.818
Oh, here we go.

00:48:44.818 --> 00:48:46.309
AUDIENCE: Hi, Mike.

00:48:46.309 --> 00:48:48.964
So you've done a lot of
research for your food, right?

00:48:48.964 --> 00:48:50.130
You've been to Israel a lot.

00:48:50.130 --> 00:48:52.830
Do you feel you have a
lot more digging to do,

00:48:52.830 --> 00:48:56.250
like find all the recipes, going
through all the genealogy, as

00:48:56.250 --> 00:48:59.560
much as the food and
recipes have traveled?

00:48:59.560 --> 00:49:01.602
Where are you in your
satisfaction level on that?

00:49:01.602 --> 00:49:03.434
MICHAEL SOLOMONOV: That
is a great question,

00:49:03.434 --> 00:49:04.829
and I am not satisfied.

00:49:04.829 --> 00:49:05.870
We have a long way to go.

00:49:05.870 --> 00:49:08.330
And I think that--

00:49:08.330 --> 00:49:17.456
god, I remembered this middle
school social studies teacher.

00:49:17.456 --> 00:49:19.830
I think it was the first--
maybe it was the first history

00:49:19.830 --> 00:49:21.310
class I ever took.

00:49:21.310 --> 00:49:24.525
And they were like, bullet
point was like, why is it

00:49:24.525 --> 00:49:25.650
important to study history?

00:49:25.650 --> 00:49:28.590
And it was like, so you can
understand or at least shape

00:49:28.590 --> 00:49:31.980
the future, which we've all
come to terms with is bullshit.

00:49:31.980 --> 00:49:38.930
But the idea of being able to
do it and figuring out your role

00:49:38.930 --> 00:49:41.380
and the sort of continuity
of it is so important.

00:49:41.380 --> 00:49:44.460
So I think that, to me,
it's part of my heritage.

00:49:44.460 --> 00:49:49.550
And I'm fascinated by the
country and what opportunities

00:49:49.550 --> 00:49:53.660
the food ways and the
cultural food ways,

00:49:53.660 --> 00:49:56.737
sort of how they
have been presented

00:49:56.737 --> 00:49:57.820
and how they can play out.

00:49:57.820 --> 00:49:59.520
I think it's very stimulating.

00:49:59.520 --> 00:50:02.390
I never get bored of it.

00:50:02.390 --> 00:50:03.954
I spent most of my life here.

00:50:03.954 --> 00:50:05.370
The moment I get
off the airplane,

00:50:05.370 --> 00:50:09.940
and I smell the orange
blossoms, and hear

00:50:09.940 --> 00:50:11.920
the country and the
people, and taste the food,

00:50:11.920 --> 00:50:15.190
and smell the spices, and
discover something new, which

00:50:15.190 --> 00:50:16.990
happens every single trip.

00:50:16.990 --> 00:50:19.630
I went five times last year.

00:50:19.630 --> 00:50:23.617
There were 30 points in those
five trips where I was like,

00:50:23.617 --> 00:50:25.450
I can't believe I've
never seen this before.

00:50:25.450 --> 00:50:27.850
I am so excited
about this thing.

00:50:27.850 --> 00:50:28.810
That never ends.

00:50:28.810 --> 00:50:36.690
And as much as I sometimes
feel so not Israeli there,

00:50:36.690 --> 00:50:40.860
I feel a sense of
peace in the bolygon,

00:50:40.860 --> 00:50:44.910
in the craziness that is Israel
that I will never get tired of.

00:50:44.910 --> 00:50:47.610
I was born there, which
means that even if I travel

00:50:47.610 --> 00:50:49.710
in the Middle East on
my American passport,

00:50:49.710 --> 00:50:52.890
it still says I was born in
Israel, which doesn't get you

00:50:52.890 --> 00:50:54.960
very far in the Middle East.

00:50:54.960 --> 00:50:58.160
But I'm really hoping--

00:50:58.160 --> 00:51:00.660
this is super cliched, but I'm
hoping that, through food, we

00:51:00.660 --> 00:51:03.930
can start to open up the
borders a little bit,

00:51:03.930 --> 00:51:05.230
figuratively and literally.

00:51:05.230 --> 00:51:07.290
It would be really amazing.

00:51:07.290 --> 00:51:12.120
I would love to be able to go
to, which I can do, go to Spain

00:51:12.120 --> 00:51:15.150
and make that sort of trek.

00:51:15.150 --> 00:51:20.790
But I would also like to be
able to go to Aleppo, what

00:51:20.790 --> 00:51:23.320
is left of it, and see
it; or go to Damascus;

00:51:23.320 --> 00:51:25.860
or to go to Beirut; or
travel through the Beqaa

00:51:25.860 --> 00:51:27.000
Valley in Lebanon.

00:51:27.000 --> 00:51:29.220
Those countries are
super important.

00:51:29.220 --> 00:51:32.100
And the fact that I
don't have access to them

00:51:32.100 --> 00:51:34.470
is infuriating, quite honestly.

00:51:34.470 --> 00:51:38.622
So hopefully, through
food, we can do it.

00:51:38.622 --> 00:51:39.580
Thank you guys so much.

00:51:39.580 --> 00:51:40.180
Thank you so much.

00:51:40.180 --> 00:51:41.221
SPEAKER: Well, thank you.

00:51:41.221 --> 00:51:44.730
[APPLAUSE]

